I found the problem. I'm using the Nvidia sound drivers you're talking about,
but there's a bug regarding a feature called &quot;CineSurround&quot; and &quot;NvMixer.&quot; It
won't turn off properly after you turn it on. I think I used it for a DVD once,
and then it got stuck on. I forgot about it.

It hadn't caused a problem with my other games, so I hadn't noticed it was
stuck on. Effectively, I think it's a 5.1 surround virtualizer, and that was
apparently crashing VTMB.

Luckily, it's easy enough to turn off with a workaround: you have to rerun the
&quot;Speaker Wizard&quot; in &quot;NvMixer.&quot; Setting the speakers back to plain &quot;2 speakers&quot;
in the dropdown does nothing, and the &quot;2 speakers (CineSurround)&quot; setting will
persist. However, full redetection sets your speakers back to regular stereo
instead of &quot;CineSurround.&quot;

Also, if you turn on *headphones* &quot;CineSurround,&quot; you'll lose the ability to
return to regular &quot;2 speaker&quot; sound. Once it's on, it's on, and you have to
rerun the wizard to get normal sound back.

But I haven't had any crashes since. :^)

Werner, you might want to stick this in a readme for the next patch, if you are
so inclined.

My symptoms were CTD's every 5-10 minutes, usually before some ambient sound
kicks in (like a door closing behind your character), and more frequently in
any place with club music playing, using Nforce on-board sound with Nvidia's
full sound drivers.

And, like a bullet, you never hear the sound that kills your game. ;^)

